## The Fallacy of Software-Based Emergency Stops
The current industry standard for autonomous agricultural and ADA robotics relies on software-polled Emergency Stops (E-Stops). This means the system checks the status of the stop button only when the operating system schedule allows it. If the CPU is bottlenecked by vision processing, navigation algorithms, or cloud latency, the physical machine continues moving. This creates a lethal delay. 

Project Ebony rejects this vulnerability. True ADA compliance requires immediate, uncompromised severing of kinetic movement.

## The Evont Hardware Interrupt Architecture
The Evont architecture employs a Zero-Latency Hardware Interrupt for all physical ADA manual overrides. The Emergency Stop circuit is wired directly to the GPIO edge-detection pins of the Jetson Orin core. 

When an operator engages the physical E-Stop, it does not wait for a software loop. It triggers an immediate hardware interrupt that bypasses the OS scheduler and severs the Pulse-Width Modulation (PWM) relays instantaneously.

